<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com – The pound extended losses against the U.S. dollar on Tuesday, falling to a two-day low after official data showed that consumer borrowing rose less-than-expected in July, while mortgage lending remained subdued.GBP/USD hit 1.6278 during European afternoon trade, the pair’s lowest since Friday; the pair subsequently consolidated at 1.6303, shedding 0.63%.Cable was likely to find support at 1.6257, the low of August 25 and resistance at 1.6453, Monday’s high.The Bank of England said net lending to individuals rose by GBP0.9 billion in July, after rising by GBP0.4 billion the previous month, disappointing expectations for a GBP1.1 billion increase.The report said net mortgage lending remained subdued, growing by GBP0.7 billion, while mortgage approvals inched up to 49,239, their highest level since May 2010.Investors remained concerned over the outlook for global growth after Federal Reserve   Chairman Ben Bernanke said Friday that there was no need for an immediate round of additional stimulus, sparking fears that the U.S. economy would continue to struggle.Elsewhere, the pound was higher against the euro, with EUR/GBP slipping 0.09% to hit 0.8835.Later in the day, the U.S. was to release data on consumer confidence as well as an industry report on house price inflation. In addition, the Federal Reserve’s Open Market Committee was to publish the minutes of its August rate-setting meeting.             ]]></raw>
